\section{Fractal Warrior (The Ninth)}

\subsection{The Story of Geometer Tolin}

\epigraph{I calculated the Ninth digit of pi. For three days, I saw the angles between thoughts. Then I forgot how to speak. The Ninth gives and takes in the same breath.}{From the confession of Geometer Tolin, Aeler Deep Vaults}

Tolin was a mathematician. He studied the Sacred Geometry—the divine ratios that spiral galaxies, the symmetry that lattices frost, the measures that turn sound into song. He was good at it. He was too good at it.

He calculated the ninth digit of pi. No one had done it before. No one has done it since. The number should not exist. It is the gap between what can be known and what cannot. Tolin looked into the gap. The gap looked back.

For three days, he saw the angles between thoughts. He could predict the fall of a leaf, the turn of a card, the trajectory of a blade before it was drawn. He could not speak. The words were there, but the order was wrong. The geometry of language had fractured.

He recovered slowly. The Ninth's gift remained—not a blessing, not a curse, but a lens. He sees the world not as it is, but as it could be. He steps where the blow will not land. He speaks the truth that ends arguments. He is never surprised.

He is never entirely present either.

\subsection{The Fracture That Remembers}

Tolin carries a broken mirror in a leather satchel. It was once a single piece, polished to perfection. He shattered it on purpose—each shard holds a different angle of the same truth. When he needs to see what is hidden, he holds a shard to his eye. The shard shows him not what is there, but what could be there. The difference is a weapon.

He has seven shards. He lost the eighth. He is not sure if he ever had it.

\subsection{The Step That Is Not There}

In battle, Tolin does not dodge. He steps where the blow will not land. This is not prediction—it is geometry. He sees the angles that others cannot see. The space between the sword and the flesh is not empty. It is a door. He steps through.

He does not know how he does this. He does not ask. The Ninth does not answer questions. It only shows.

\subsection{The River at Dawn}

Tolin was present at the Black River when the locket was returned. He did not interfere. He only watched—from an angle that should not exist, at a time that was not quite dawn. He saw the ghost with the brass hook. He saw the knight with the silver gauntlet. He saw the locket sink.

He did not speak. The Ninth had given him a glimpse of what the locket contained—not hair, not thread, but a name. The name was not for him. He did not write it down. The Ninth does not permit witnesses to betray their witness.

He left before the sun rose. His shadow followed a half-step behind.

\subsection{What the Fractal Warrior Carries}

A Fractal Warrior carries broken mirrors and impossible angles. They carry the weight of what they have seen and cannot speak. They carry the knowledge that the future is not fixed—it is a branching tree, and they can see the branches.

But most of all, they carry the certainty that some doors should not be opened, some numbers should not be calculated, and some angles should not be seen. The Ninth does not warn. It only shows.

\vspace{1em}
\begin{center}
\textit{The thread held. The water carried. That is not a Rite. That is grace.}
\end{center}

\section{Fractal Warrior (The Ninth)}

\subsection{Concept}

The Fractal Warrior is a warrior who fights with impossible angles and precognition. They do not rely on strength or speed—they rely on geometry. They see the trajectory of a blade before it is drawn. They step where the blow will not land. They speak truths that end arguments because they have already seen the outcome.

Their Codex is a broken mirror or a fractal slate. Their Thiasos is a pattern-spirit that shows glimpses of the future, a memory-spirit that records what has not yet happened, or a sentient shard that whispers angles. Their Rites are not declarations—they are corrections. The world is wrong. The Fractal Warrior sets it right.

A Fractal Warrior is never entirely present. They are always a half-step ahead, or a half-step behind. The Ninth does not permit stillness.

\subsection{Core Attributes}

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Primary:} Wits, Spirit
\item \textbf{Secondary:} Body
\item \textbf{Tertiary:} Presence
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Skills}

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Core:} Lore (Geometry), Insight, Investigation
\item \textbf{Secondary:} Melee, Athletics, Survival
\item \textbf{Tertiary:} Arcana, Stealth
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Codex}

The Fractal Warrior's Codex is a testament to broken perception:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Broken Mirror:} A shattered mirror, carried in a leather satchel. Each shard shows a different angle. Holding a shard to the eye reveals hidden patterns (gaining +1 die to Investigation or Insight).
\item \textbf{Fractal Slate:} A slate tablet covered in spiraling, unfinished equations. The equations change—constantly—as the Ninth recalculates. The slate is never complete.
\item \textbf{Angle Lens:} A brass-and-glass lens cut with a faceted surface. Looking through it shows the world not as it is, but as it could be. Disorienting. Useful.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Thiasos}

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Pattern-Spirit:} A translucent form of shifting geometry—spirals, fractals, impossible angles. It can show a glimpse of the future: once per session, the GM must answer a yes/no question about an upcoming roll. Cap 2, Harm 3.
\item \textbf{Memory-Echo:} A spirit that cannot speak, but can replay sounds it has witnessed—including sounds that have not happened yet. The GM decides what it "remembers." Cap 2, Harm 3.
\item \textbf{The Fractal Slate (Sentient):} A slate that speaks in overlapping voices. Can predict the outcome of a single roll (the GM must answer "success" or "failure" before the roll). (See Optional Rule: Sentient Thiasos)
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Signature Rites}

\subsubsection{Low Rite: Rite of the Ninth Figure (4 XP)}

\textbf{Tags:} [KNOWLEDGE], [THRESHOLD]

Glimpse past the ordinary frame of measure. Gain +1 die to Lore or Investigation when wrestling complex systems or many-layered problems.

\subsubsection{Low Rite: Rite of the Unseen Angle (5 XP)}

\textbf{Tags:} [PREDICTION], [BOOST]

You see the trajectory of a blade before it is drawn. For one scene, gain +1 die to defense rolls against melee attacks. You cannot be surprised by a visible enemy.

\subsubsection{Standard Rite: Rite of the Hypercognitive Lattice (8 XP)}

\textbf{Tags:} [BOOST], [THRESHOLD], [OVERFLOW]

Widen the mind's mouth. For this scene, treat your Wits as +2 higher for information-processing rolls; you may track several intricate streams at once.

\subsubsection{Standard Rite: Rite of the Breaking Glyph (7 XP)}

\textbf{Tags:} [KNOWLEDGE], [TRUTH], [THRESHOLD]

Take one pattern whole. Choose a complex system, theory, or design and gain perfect internal grasp of it; receive +3 dice to related knowledge rolls for the session.

\subsubsection{High Rite: Rite of the Ninth Revelation (14 XP)}

\textbf{Tags:} [TRUTH], [THRESHOLD], [TRANSFORM], [FATE]

Glimpse a shard of Ninth truth. Take one major insight that overleaps common frames—perfect command of a knotty system, forecast of chaotic motion, or comprehension of an "impossible" relation.

\subsection{Signature Talents}

\subsubsection{Glimpse Beyond (4 XP)}

\textbf{Requirement:} The Ninth

Once per session, look at a complex situation (a crime scene, a puzzle lock, a battle formation) and instantly intuit the single most important hidden detail. The GM gives you one piece of information that would otherwise require a successful Investigation roll. Mark 1 Fatigue after using this talent.

\subsubsection{Fractal Step (6 XP)}

\textbf{Requirement:} The Ninth, Wits 3+

Once per scene, when you are attacked, you may step where the blow will not land. Treat your Position as one step higher (Desperate → Controlled, Controlled → Dominant) for that defense. You must declare this before the roll.

\subsubsection{Pattern Recognition (8 XP)}

\textbf{Requirement:} The Ninth, Tier II+

You see patterns in everything—the way dust falls, the arrangement of stones, the spacing of guards. Once per session, you may ask the GM one yes/no question about a pattern or hidden connection in the current scene. The GM must answer truthfully.

